Execution Plan
Phase 1: Types and Interfaces
Step 1.1: Extend analytics event taxonomy for experiments, dunning lifecycle, expansion nudges, and CWV metrics in src/services/analytics.ts.
Step 1.2: Define experiment contract (variant keys, assignment source, allowed surfaces) used by landing + wizard + scanner.
Step 1.3: Define churn recovery payload shape (reason, offer_shown, offer_accepted, channel, outcome) in PMF service boundaries.
Step 1.4: Define CWV telemetry event schema (LCP/INP/CLS/TTFB/FCP route attribution) in client instrumentation interfaces.
Verify: Typecheck passes for the new contracts before touching behavior.
Phase 2: Profitability Optimization (Highest Revenue Impact)
Step 2.1: Implement paywall/pricing experiment assignment + event capture wiring (PricingPlans, DashboardWizard, ScannerPanel, analytics/track API).
Step 2.2: Add conversion-optimized expansion triggers (usage threshold nudges and contextual upgrade CTAs) in scanner/wizard surfaces.
Step 2.3: Implement churn save flow in ChurnSurveyForm + pmf/churn route (offer presentation + acceptance tracking before billing-portal handoff).
Step 2.4: Improve Stripe webhook dunning hooks (invoice.payment_failed, retries, recovery-state transitions, analytics emissions).
Step 2.5: Ensure PMF dashboard exposes new funnel + retention/recovery metrics (src/lib/pmf/service.ts, /dashboard/pmf).
Verify: checkout, churn submit, dunning transitions, and PMF aggregate metrics all behave correctly in tests and manual route checks.
Phase 3: Loading Speed Optimization (Highest UX/CVR Impact)
Step 3.1: Finalize third-party script governance (lazy/idle loading, non-blocking init, no critical-path impact) across layout + analytics components.
Step 3.2: Add route-level CWV telemetry from client instrumentation into analytics pipeline.
Step 3.3: Add practical performance guardrails (cache/header improvements where safe, stricter no-store only where required).
Step 3.4: Add CI performance budget check strategy (build artifact or Lighthouse/Web Vitals gate as supported by repo tooling).
Verify: no regression in app functionality; telemetry events emitted; build/tests remain green.
Phase 4: SEO Completion Pass (After Profitability + Speed)
Step 4.1: Re-audit landing SEO and fill any remaining gaps (metadata consistency, canonical integrity, OG/Twitter completeness, section anchors).
Step 4.2: Ensure structured data alignment with visible content and entity linking completeness in StructuredData.tsx.
Step 4.3: Validate sitemap.ts and robots.ts against intended crawl/index strategy for all public pages.
Step 4.4: Strengthen internal linking where relevant (landing → blog/compare/money pages) without over-linking.
Verify: title/meta/schema/sitemap/robots outputs are correct and consistent with public route intent.
Phase 5: Tests and End-to-End Validation
Step 5.1: Update/add tests for analytics events, pricing/paywall behavior, churn recovery, dunning transitions, and scanner upsell paths.
Step 5.2: Run full quality gate and fix regressions.
Verify: Run npm run typecheck && npm run lint && npm run test && npm run build.
Phase 6: Deployment Readiness
Step 6.1: Confirm required env vars for experiments, Stripe/dunning, analytics, and telemetry are documented and validated.
Step 6.2: Produce deployment checklist and run smoke checks on key routes (/, /dashboard, /dashboard/home, checkout/churn APIs).
Step 6.3: Execute deployment through existing pipeline (or hand off exact release steps if deployment permissions are restricted).
Verify: post-deploy smoke confirms no regression in conversion-critical and performance-critical paths.
Rollback Plan
If something fails:

Revert Phase 2 profitability behavior behind feature flags/variant default fallback to current control behavior.
Revert script-loading and telemetry changes in Phase 3 to previous stable loader strategy.
Revert webhook/dunning behavior to prior entitlement update flow if billing state anomalies appear.
Keep SEO-only improvements isolated so they can stay even if profitability/performance code is rolled back.
Risks
Billing-state regressions in Stripe webhook changes → Mitigate with idempotent handlers, narrow status transitions, and targeted tests.
Experiment logic impacting conversion unintentionally → Mitigate with control-default fallback and explicit variant allowlist validation.
Telemetry overhead harming performance → Mitigate with sampled, async, fire-and-forget client reporting.
SEO/schema drift from on-page content → Mitigate by reusing shared data sources and adding tests for schema-visible content consistency.
Deployment env mismatch → Mitigate with startup validation and pre-deploy env checklist.
